<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-03-17T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-03-17T04:00:00-05:00" n="941" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d941">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/20395:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Thurston</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi><note n="47" xml:id="d941fn47">Repeated to the Ambassador in Turkey
                                as Department’s telegram No. 85, March 19, 4 p.m.</note>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Kuibyshev</hi> (<hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>)</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-03-17T12:00:00+03:00">March 17,
                                1942—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 12:48 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>232. I informed Vyshinski<note n="48" xml:id="d941fn48">Andrey
                                Yanuaryevich Vyshinsky, Assistant People’s Commissar for Foreign
                                Affairs of the Soviet Union.</note> last night of the report
                            regarding the recent attempt on Von Papen’s life as presented in the
                            Department’s 122, March 14.<note n="49" xml:id="d941fn49">See footnote
                                43, <ref target="#pg_825">p. 825</ref>.</note> Vyshinski expressed
                            great appreciation, and said the information confirmed other reports
                            reaching the Soviet Government indicative of efforts by Germany to
                            provoke a conflict between Russia and Turkey.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Thurston</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>